etymologies: early 20th century; earliest use found in Bulletin Natal Department Agriculture. From sub- + dwarf

definitions: A tree, especially a cultivar, that is smaller than a size regarded as dwarf. Compare "dwarf".

A star which lies just below the main sequence on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram, being less luminous than main sequence stars of the same temperature or spectral type. Also "subdwarf star". Compare "dwarf", subgiant.
